{
  "id": "ellis_bronnikov",
  "name": "Ellis-Bronnikov",
  "description": "A static, spherically symmetric traversable wormhole with zero redshift function, also known as the drainhole metric.",
  "tags": [
    "wormhole",
    "exotic matter",
    "traversable",
    "static",
    "spherically symmetric",
    "stationary"
  ],
  "signature": "(-,+,+,+)",
  "convention": "The time coordinate is $ct$. The coordinate $r$ is the proper radial distance, $r \\in (-\\infty,\\infty)$, with the wormhole throat at $r = 0$. The parameter $\\ell > 0$ is the throat radius.",
  "history": "The Morris-Thorne wormhole was introduced by Michael Morris and Kip Thorne in 1988 as a framework for studying traversable wormholes within classical general relativity. Their paper, originally motivated by a question from Carl Sagan during the writing of the novel Contact, identified the conditions a wormhole metric must satisfy to be traversable by human travelers: no horizons, tidal forces tolerable to a human, and a traversal time short enough to be practical. The key result was that all traversable wormholes require exotic matter — stress-energy that violates the null energy condition, meaning some observer measures negative energy densities. This placed traversable wormholes in a theoretically consistent but physically problematic category, since no classical matter field satisfies the exotic matter condition.¶The simplified form of the metric given here — sometimes called the Ellis wormhole or the zero-tidal-force wormhole — sets the redshift function $\\Phi = 0$ and takes the shape function $b(r) = \\ell^2/r$, which in proper distance coordinates gives the particularly clean form $ds^2 = -c^2dt^2 + dr^2 + (r^2 + \\ell^2)d\\Omega^2$. This metric is geodesically complete, manifestly symmetric between the two asymptotically flat regions ($r \\to \\pm\\infty$), and is a standard homework problem in graduate GR courses. Despite the simplicity of the metric, the Einstein tensor is nonzero and requires exotic matter as its source.",
  "references": [
    "morris1988",
    "ellis1973",
    "visser1995",
    "misner1973"
  ],
